    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-12-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="292"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d292">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation, lot 64 D
                    199</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of State</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d292fn1">The original of this memorandum was transmitted to
                        Admiral <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1">Strauss</persName> on Dec.
                        14.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1954-12-14">December 14,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum of Conversation with Mr. <persName
                            corresp="#p_MURRAYTE1">Thomas Murray</persName> Monday, December 13,
                        1954—3:55 p.m.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The conversation lasted only for 5 minutes because there was confusion about the
                    appointment, and I had another engagement. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MURRAYTE1"
                        >Murray</persName> said that he thought there could be a moratorium on all
                    thermonuclear, as distinct from atomic, explosions and that this would be in the
                    interests of the US. He said that it was possible to distinguish between atomic
                    and thermonuclear explosions so that this would not involve fixing a magnitude
                    limit which might interfere <pb facs="0771" n="1585" xml:id="pg_1585"/> with
                    atomic experimentation. Also, it would be easily susceptible of independent
                    verification. I thanked Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MURRAYTE1">Murray</persName>
                    for his ideas.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">John Foster Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
